**Fibonacci Number Calculation using Recursion in C++**

The Fibonacci sequence is a series of numbers in which each number is the sum of the two preceding ones, usually starting with 0 and 1.

### Code

```cpp
#include <iostream>

/**
 * Function to calculate the nth Fibonacci number using recursion.
 * 
 * @param n The position of the Fibonacci number to calculate.
 * @return The nth Fibonacci number.
 */
int fibonacci(int n) {
    // Base cases: F(0) = 0, F(1) = 1
    if (n == 0) {
        return 0;
    } else if (n == 1) {
        return 1;
    } else {
        // Recursive case: F(n) = F(n-1) + F(n-2)
        return fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2);
    }
}

int main() {
    int n;
    std::cout << "Enter the position of the Fibonacci number: ";
    std::cin >> n;

    if (n < 0) {
        std::cout << "Error: n must be a non-negative integer." << std::endl;
    } else {
        int result = fibonacci(n);
        std::cout << "The " << n << "th Fibonacci number is: " << result << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

### Explanation

This C++ program uses a recursive function `fibonacci(n)` to calculate the nth Fibonacci number. The function follows the standard Fibonacci sequence formula:

- `F(0) = 0`
- `F(1) = 1`
- `F(n) = F(n-1) + F(n-2)` for `n > 1`

The `main()` function prompts the user to enter the position of the Fibonacci number to calculate. It then calls the `fibonacci(n)` function with the user-input value and prints the result.

### Example Use Cases

- For `n = 5`, the output will be: `The 5th Fibonacci number is: 5`
- For `n = 8`, the output will be: `The 8th Fibonacci number is: 21`
- For `n = 0`, the output will be: `The 0th Fibonacci number is: 0`
- For `n = 1`, the output will be: `The 1st Fibonacci number is: 1`

### Note

This recursive solution is not the most efficient way to calculate Fibonacci numbers for large values of `n`, as it involves a lot of repeated calculations. For larger values, consider using an iterative solution or a memoization technique to optimize performance.

**Sequence Calculation using Recursion in C++**

This sequence is known as the Tribonacci sequence, a generalization of the Fibonacci sequence. Each term in the Tribonacci sequence is the sum of the three preceding ones, starting with 0, -1, -1.

### Code

```cpp
#include <iostream>

/**
 * Function to calculate the nth Tribonacci number using recursion.
 * 
 * @param n The position of the Tribonacci number to calculate.
 * @return The nth Tribonacci number.
 */
int tribonacci(int n) {
    // Base cases: T(0) = 0, T(1) = -1, T(2) = -1
    if (n == 0) {
        return 0;
    } else if (n == 1) {
        return -1;
    } else if (n == 2) {
        return -1;
    } else {
        // Recursive case: T(n) = T(n-1) + T(n-2) + T(n-3)
        return tribonacci(n - 1) + tribonacci(n - 2) + tribonacci(n - 3);
    }
}

int main() {
    int n;
    std::cout << "Enter the position of the Tribonacci number: ";
    std::cin >> n;

    if (n < 0) {
        std::cout << "Error: n must be a non-negative integer." << std::endl;
    } else {
        int result = tribonacci(n);
        std::cout << "The " << n << "th Tribonacci number is: " << result << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

### Explanation

This C++ program uses a recursive function `tribonacci(n)` to calculate the nth Tribonacci number. The function follows the standard Tribonacci sequence formula:

- `T(0) = 0`
- `T(1) = -1`
- `T(2) = -1`
- `T(n) = T(n-1) + T(n-2) + T(n-3)` for `n > 2`

The `main()` function prompts the user to enter the position of the Tribonacci number to calculate. It then calls the `tribonacci(n)` function with the user-input value and prints the result.

### Example Use Cases

- For `n = 5`, the output will be: `The 5th Tribonacci number is: 0`
- For `n = 8`, the output will be: `The 8th Tribonacci number is: 4`
- For `n = 0`, the output will be: `The 0th Tribonacci number is: 0`
- For `n = 1`, the output will be: `The 1st Tribonacci number is: -1`
- For `n = 2`, the output will be: `The 2nd Tribonacci number is: -1`

### Note

This recursive solution is not the most efficient way to calculate Tribonacci numbers for large values of `n`, as it involves a lot of repeated calculations. For larger values, consider using an iterative solution or a memoization technique to optimize performance.

**Simple Joke Website**

Below is a simple HTML website that displays a random joke when a button is clicked.

### HTML Code
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Joke Website</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            text-align: center;
        }

        #joke {
            font-size: 24px;
            font-weight: bold;
        }

        button {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            font-size: 16px;
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            color: #fff;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }

        button:hover {
            background-color: #3e8e41;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Joke Website</h1>
    <div id="joke"></div>
    <button onclick="displayJoke()">Get Joke</button>

    <script>
        // Array of jokes
        const jokes = [
            {
                id: 1,
                joke: "Why don't scientists trust atoms? Because they make up everything."
            },
            {
                id: 2,
                joke: "Why don't eggs tell jokes? They'd crack each other up."
            },
            {
                id: 3,
                joke: "Why don't lobsters share? Because they're shellfish."
            },
            {
                id: 4,
                joke: "What do you call a fake noodle? An impasta."
            }
        ];

        // Function to display a random joke
        function displayJoke() {
            // Get a random joke from the array
            const randomJoke = jokes[Math.floor(Math.random() * jokes.length)];

            // Display the joke
            document.getElementById("joke").innerHTML = `Joke ${randomJoke.id}: ${randomJoke.joke}`;
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### How it works

1. The website has a button with the text "Get Joke".
2. When the button is clicked, the `displayJoke()` function is called.
3. The `displayJoke()` function selects a random joke from the `jokes` array using the `Math.random()` function.
4. The selected joke is then displayed on the webpage by updating the `innerHTML` of the `#joke` div.

### Example Use Case

* Open the website in a web browser.
* Click the "Get Joke" button to display a random joke.
* Click the "Get Joke" button again to display another random joke.

